data.survey.strategy: I kept the information organized
i looked at the facts that showed up the most consistently
First gather the most relevant facts and then filter by what's related to those.
Move the clues around until they made sense.
I tried my best to find the real clues
Looking at what the collaborators had on their notebooks, and looking for similarities with what I had.  Then reading the rest of the leads, and seeing if any contradicted eachother.
go with the most common evidence
I looked at clues that made the most sense.
Looking for 2 or more clues that collaborated each other
read each clue, pick the ones with the highest likelihood based on number of incidence
i read the clues and thought about which made the most sense
I tried to look at the big picture of the story then see it as it happened. I then linked the clues to each other, fleshing out the entire scenario.
I tried to parse through the information to see what seemed to connect more or have more related information or the kind of information that showed up more often.
I tried to see how many clues were similar and what clues had little to do with the description
When things kept being mentioned, I gave them more weight than something that was mentioned once or twice.
I started off with the watch and then the clues that came in I categorized by what I thought was possible and not possible.
My strategy was to read the clues as quick as I could and try to decide which ones came up more often , and which pieces of evidence were in the different clues.
I tried to go off what I thought was stronger evidence. For example, if the police said they identified a certain tool was used, I started looking for other clues that had tools in them.
trying to tie together as many clues together as possible
I put clues in the "promising leads" category if they included names and words like "was seen" instead of "thought they saw".
Not entirely sure- kind of a scramble at first

Seeing what sounded most plausible (for example, a circular saw would not be used to disable an alarm system - that's so large and clunky), and I looked for consistency. Consistent clues that chained together seemed more plausible to me.
My strategy was to sort out the clues that seemed related to the case and pick and choose which ones had the most correlations.
I looked at each clue, and if it was very generic, I moved it to the bottom. If it gave information, or was linked to another clue, I put it at the top.
see which clues seem realistic
Use as many clues as possible without getting penalized by putting them in the wrong category
I tried to pick out which clues were found in multiple accounts and work off that
Look over all the clues and see if there is any conflicting clues
I was watching my teammates and also trying to figure out what made the most sense to me. I'm still a little confused how the game works or how I received the bonuses.
Process of elimination
Compare evidences for each individual suspect and choose the suspect with the most supporting evidences
eval all clues

I tried to narrow the clues down based on witness statements and evidence from the estate but I didn't have enough time to thoroughly think through all the clues so most of them were promising but needed more investigation.
just put the facts in order and grouped where it made sense
I did my best to make sense of the clues in order to form a plausible story.
tried to see what was selected the most between all.
i went with clues that matched clues i already had.
Anything that was backed up by others seemed more likely to be a clue.
I tried to categorize the different clues and then cross check them and eliminate.
